<i>♪ Band camp calls tonight ♪</i>

30
00:01:47,440 --> 00:01:50,690
<i>♪ My demo goes online ♪</i>

31
00:01:50,777 --> 00:01:54,107
<i>♪ Tonight ♪</i>

32
00:01:54,197 --> 00:01:56,987
♪ ♪

33
00:02:07,293 --> 00:02:10,173
<i>♪ Tonight, tonight ♪</i>

34
00:02:10,255 --> 00:02:13,545
<i>♪ My dreams come true tonight ♪</i>

35
00:02:13,633 --> 00:02:16,723
<i>-LISA: ♪ Deposit's due tonight ♪</i>
<i>-HOMER: ♪ I'll take the pot tonight ♪</i>

36
00:02:16,803 --> 00:02:18,473
<i>ALL:</i>
<i>♪ Tonight! ♪</i>

37
00:02:21,391 --> 00:02:23,231
{\an8}Moe, what the hell is that?!

38
00:02:23,309 --> 00:02:25,019
Sorry. I missed rehearsal.

39
00:02:25,770 --> 00:02:27,480
MOE:
Damn it.

40
00:02:27,564 --> 00:02:29,574
{\an8}Marge, I'm heading out!
Poker night!

41
00:02:30,817 --> 00:02:33,737
{\an8}I don't want you losing
all our scrimpings!

42
00:02:33,820 --> 00:02:35,110
{\an8}Don't worry, Marge.

43
00:02:35,196 --> 00:02:37,446
{\an8}The real excitement for me
is staying within a budget.

44
00:02:37,532 --> 00:02:38,742
{\an8}(snickers)

45
00:02:38,825 --> 00:02:41,155
{\an8}This is just a friendly game, right?

46
00:02:41,244 --> 00:02:43,664
{\an8}Oh, super friendly.

47
00:02:43,746 --> 00:02:45,076
Suckers.

48
00:02:45,165 --> 00:02:46,615
Dad, Dad, Dad.

49
00:02:46,708 --> 00:02:49,498
{\an8}I need two things:
a good-night hug and a favor.

50
00:02:49,586 --> 00:02:51,246
{\an8}-Mm.
-To save time,

51
00:02:51,337 --> 00:02:52,797
{\an8}I'll start describing the favor.

52
00:02:52,881 --> 00:02:55,091
{\an8}I've just been accepted
to the best band camp

53
00:02:55,175 --> 00:02:57,215
{\an8}this side of the Mississippi!

54
00:02:57,302 --> 00:02:58,722
{\an8}Which side are we again?

55
00:02:58,803 --> 00:03:00,893
{\an8}Doesn't matter!
It's a great camp.

56
00:03:00,972 --> 00:03:03,392
{\an8}Notable graduates include Pete Barbutti.

57
00:03:03,474 --> 00:03:04,644
{\an8}Pete Barbutti?!

58
00:03:04,726 --> 00:03:06,596
{\an8}Yes! Anyway, it's a little pricey.

59
00:03:06,686 --> 00:03:08,436
{\an8}So, if you win big tonight,

60
00:03:08,521 --> 00:03:11,731
{\an8}maybe you could help make
a little girl really happy.

61
00:03:11,816 --> 00:03:13,476
{\an8}Don't worry, sweetie,
I'm gonna win.

62
00:03:13,568 --> 00:03:15,988
{\an8}And you know why?

63
00:03:16,070 --> 00:03:18,950
{\an8}I'm wearing my lucky T-shirt.

64
00:03:19,032 --> 00:03:21,162
{\an8}(sighs)
It was such a shame

65
00:03:21,242 --> 00:03:23,832
{\an8}he lost to President Garfield.

66
00:03:25,330 --> 00:03:27,870
{\an8}Oh, I'll fix this.

67
00:03:29,918 --> 00:03:30,958
{\an8}There.

68
00:03:31,044 --> 00:03:32,344
{\an8}(hums a tune)

69
00:03:33,463 --> 00:03:36,053
{\an8}The maestro is here.

70
00:03:36,132 --> 00:03:38,302
{\an8}-(screams)
-(crashes)

71
00:03:38,384 --> 00:03:40,474
{\an8}-Hey, who's the lady?
-What, are you kidding?

72
00:03:40,553 --> 00:03:42,933
{\an8}This is Laney Fontaine,
Broadway legend.

73
00:03:43,014 --> 00:03:44,684
{\an8}She starred opposite Al Pacino

74
00:03:44,766 --> 00:03:46,636
{\an8}in <i>Does a Tiger Wear A Necktie?</i>

75
00:03:46,726 --> 00:03:47,596
{\an8}Ooh!

76
00:03:47,685 --> 00:03:48,975
{\an8}Now I date Moe.

77
00:03:49,062 --> 00:03:50,982
{\an8}He's got everything I look for in a man:

78
00:03:51,064 --> 00:03:52,824
{\an8}a current liquor license.

79
00:03:52,899 --> 00:03:54,649
{\an8}(chuckles)
Well, it and you

80
00:03:54,734 --> 00:03:57,904
{\an8}are the two most precious
wrinkled yellow things I know.

81
00:03:58,738 --> 00:04:00,778
{\an8}♪ ♪

82
00:04:06,412 --> 00:04:08,672
{\an8}<i>WOMAN (over headphones):</i>
<i>Three of a kind beats two pair.</i>

83
00:04:08,748 --> 00:04:10,378
{\an8}<i>Straight beats three of a kind.</i>

84
00:04:10,458 --> 00:04:11,998
{\an8}<i>Three beats two.</i>

85
00:04:12,085 --> 00:04:13,415
{\an8}<i>Four beats three.</i>

86
00:04:13,503 --> 00:04:14,593
{\an8}(dog howling)

87
00:04:18,591 --> 00:04:20,301
{\an8}<i>HOMER:</i>
<i>Oh, my God.</i>

88
00:04:20,385 --> 00:04:22,755
{\an8}<i>Full house.</i>

89
00:04:22,845 --> 00:04:26,135
{\an8}We're gonna win!
That means Lisa goes to band camp.

90
00:04:26,224 --> 00:04:28,184
{\an8}As long as Homer doesn't let them know

91
00:04:28,268 --> 00:04:30,398
{\an8}how good his hand is.

92
00:04:30,478 --> 00:04:32,858
{\an8}Then he'll blow
the whole damn thing to hell!

93
00:04:32,939 --> 00:04:34,519
{\an8}That would be terrible.

94
00:04:34,607 --> 00:04:37,647
{\an8}Worst jammed-in movie parody ever.

95
00:04:37,735 --> 00:04:39,985
{\an8}Come on, Homer. Poker face.

96
00:04:41,990 --> 00:04:44,370
{\an8}Aah! Stupid git!

97
00:04:44,450 --> 00:04:47,000
{\an8}I raise, no calls, pot goes to me.

98
00:04:47,078 --> 00:04:48,828
{\an8}Hold on, Fat Folds Five.

99
00:04:48,913 --> 00:04:50,043
{\an8}(stammers)

100
00:04:50,123 --> 00:04:52,883
{\an8}I see your raise, and I raise this.

101
00:04:53,960 --> 00:04:55,920
Is that real?

102
00:04:56,004 --> 00:04:57,514
Won it for cinematography.

103
00:04:57,588 --> 00:05:00,628
Invented a new kind of Steadicam
that's mounted on a dog.

104
00:05:00,717 --> 00:05:02,927
That's five grand to you.

105
00:05:03,011 --> 00:05:05,891
So, are you in, or are you...

106
00:05:05,972 --> 00:05:07,562
(groans)

107
00:05:07,640 --> 00:05:10,480
While I'm out, no one
look at my cards or my boobs.

108
00:05:10,560 --> 00:05:11,810
(groans)

109
00:05:11,894 --> 00:05:14,404
Aw.
Don't she black out like an angel?

110
00:05:14,480 --> 00:05:16,230
Queens beat jacks.

111
00:05:16,316 --> 00:05:17,726
No one heard that.
I'm in.

112
00:05:17,817 --> 00:05:20,067
(hums a tune)

113
00:05:24,824 --> 00:05:27,334
Okay, Homer.
Moment of truth.

114
00:05:30,330 --> 00:05:32,920
Oh, four of a kind!
Hey, honey, you won!

115
00:05:32,999 --> 00:05:33,999
Huh?

116
00:05:34,083 --> 00:05:35,423
I lost.

117
00:05:35,501 --> 00:05:37,841
I lost everything.

118
00:05:37,920 --> 00:05:39,800
We're gonna celebrate, Moe.

119
00:05:39,881 --> 00:05:42,971
-What's Springfield's version of Sardi's?
-Uh, Hardee's.

120
00:05:43,051 --> 00:05:46,601
I know a nice booth
under a picture of a hamburger. Heh.

121
00:05:46,679 --> 00:05:49,099
Aw, come on, Homer.
I'll drive you home.

122
00:05:49,182 --> 00:05:51,062
(imitates engine revving)

123
00:05:51,142 --> 00:05:52,852
Hey, off we go!

124
00:05:52,935 --> 00:05:55,015
Vroom, vroom, vroom.

125
00:05:55,104 --> 00:05:56,274
(imitates engine chugging)

126
00:05:56,356 --> 00:05:57,936
(door closes)

127
00:05:58,024 --> 00:06:00,534
<i>WOMAN: You've completed</i>
Poker: A Beginner's Guide.

128
00:06:00,610 --> 00:06:03,360
<i>Now go out there and win.</i>

129
00:06:03,446 --> 00:06:05,446
I bid two bucks.

130
00:06:15,708 --> 00:06:17,208
(floor creaking softly)

131
00:06:22,423 --> 00:06:24,053
-(belt cracks)
-(gasps) What was that?

132
00:06:24,133 --> 00:06:27,513
Those aren't the tiptoes
of a successful gambler.

133
00:06:27,595 --> 00:06:29,425
How much did you lose?

134
00:06:29,514 --> 00:06:30,814
$5,000.

135
00:06:30,890 --> 00:06:31,970
(high-pitched chirping)

136
00:06:32,058 --> 00:06:33,678
Whoa, I never heard that noise.

137
00:06:33,768 --> 00:06:35,598
(sobbing)

138
00:06:35,686 --> 00:06:36,976
(Marge continues sobbing)

139
00:06:37,063 --> 00:06:41,193
I'm just sayin', doesn't look like
band camp is in the cards.

140
00:06:42,777 --> 00:06:44,777
(playing jazz)

141
00:06:47,073 --> 00:06:48,953
Hey, this is my thing now.

142
00:06:51,577 --> 00:06:52,947
So easy.

143
00:06:53,037 --> 00:06:54,577
Guys, I need help with a plan.

144
00:06:54,664 --> 00:06:56,374
Hey, what about a reverse mortgage?

145
00:06:56,457 --> 00:06:59,167
I saw a commercial for one
where an old lady gave a thumbs-up

146
00:06:59,252 --> 00:07:01,922
and it turned into money,
which filled up the screen.

147
00:07:02,004 --> 00:07:03,304
The entire screen?

148
00:07:03,381 --> 00:07:04,881
Swear to God.

149
00:07:04,966 --> 00:07:07,886
Hey, Homer, here's a thought:
invite Laney over for dinner.

150
00:07:07,969 --> 00:07:11,009
Show her your crummy home,
your unhappy kids.

151
00:07:11,097 --> 00:07:13,017
Anyone with a heart would take pity.

152
00:07:13,099 --> 00:07:15,099
Finally, my sucky life pays off.

153
00:07:15,184 --> 00:07:16,734
Do you guys think she'll buy it?

154
00:07:16,811 --> 00:07:19,611
Oh, yeah. Your whole house, uh,
it smells like a basement.

155
00:07:19,689 --> 00:07:21,359
I've always hated your rugs.

156
00:07:21,441 --> 00:07:23,861
Yeah... Whoa, whoa, whoa.
Why you have to go there, man?

157
00:07:23,943 --> 00:07:25,453
He has such beautiful floors.

158
00:07:25,528 --> 00:07:27,608
Why must he hide them? Why?

159
00:07:27,697 --> 00:07:28,947
LANEY:
There I am,

160
00:07:29,031 --> 00:07:30,781
on the main stage at Caesar's,

161
00:07:30,867 --> 00:07:32,577
about to sing "Do You Love Me,"

162
00:07:32,660 --> 00:07:35,200
when who do I see sitting in the wings?

163
00:07:35,288 --> 00:07:37,038
Your boyfriend King Tut?

164
00:07:37,123 --> 00:07:38,923
No. Jack Jones.

165
00:07:39,000 --> 00:07:40,790
High on his success
from "Wives and Lovers"

166
00:07:40,877 --> 00:07:43,707
with eyes for yours truly.

167
00:07:43,796 --> 00:07:47,126
But you'd just accepted
a proposal from Mike Connors.

168
00:07:47,216 --> 00:07:48,716
Which I broke off.

169
00:07:48,801 --> 00:07:51,261
Let's just say
Mannix was the one man

170
00:07:51,345 --> 00:07:53,095
I had to nix.

171
00:07:53,181 --> 00:07:55,101
(laughs)
Oh!

172
00:07:55,183 --> 00:07:56,733
Oh, that's rich!

173
00:07:56,809 --> 00:07:57,769
Oh, my God.

174
00:07:57,852 --> 00:07:58,982
That's going in your book.

175
00:07:59,061 --> 00:08:00,611
Please tell me you're writing a book.

176
00:08:00,688 --> 00:08:02,568
(choking)

177
00:08:02,648 --> 00:08:03,978
(grunts)
Sit down, boy.

178
00:08:04,066 --> 00:08:05,396
We're trying to show this dame

179
00:08:05,485 --> 00:08:06,985
that we're deserving of her pity.

180
00:08:07,069 --> 00:08:08,319
Where's that crutch I gave you?

181
00:08:08,404 --> 00:08:10,074
There's nothing wrong with my leg.

182
00:08:10,156 --> 00:08:11,156
There will be.

183
00:08:11,240 --> 00:08:12,330
D'oh!

184
00:08:12,408 --> 00:08:14,698
Ow! Ow, my leg!

185
00:08:16,037 --> 00:08:19,327
(sobbing)
Oh! Oh, my leg.

186
00:08:19,415 --> 00:08:20,915
Oh!

187
00:08:21,000 --> 00:08:24,920
Who would take $5,000
from such a miserable creature?

188
00:08:25,004 --> 00:08:27,514
(sobbing)

189
00:08:27,590 --> 00:08:30,130
Laney, I know it's your night off,

190
00:08:30,218 --> 00:08:32,548
but would you like
to sing a song for us?

191
00:08:32,637 --> 00:08:34,637
You don't have to ask me twice.

192
00:08:34,722 --> 00:08:39,312
<i>♪ I'm just a Broadway lady ♪</i>

193
00:08:40,978 --> 00:08:44,478
<i>♪ Dancing on my aching feet ♪</i>

194
00:08:46,609 --> 00:08:50,149
<i>♪ Avoiding any foods with wheat ♪</i>

195
00:08:50,238 --> 00:08:54,328
<i>♪ And no drinking pre-show ♪</i>

196
00:08:54,408 --> 00:08:56,038
It's okay if the producer don't...

197
00:08:56,118 --> 00:08:59,368
<i>♪ Know ♪</i>

198
00:08:59,455 --> 00:09:01,535
(playing jazz)

199
00:09:05,795 --> 00:09:08,375
Wow.
You know your way around a horn, kid.

200
00:09:08,464 --> 00:09:10,134
Oh, listen, I don't want to gush,

201
00:09:10,216 --> 00:09:11,836
but I have all your albums--

202
00:09:11,926 --> 00:09:13,136
<i>Laney Sings The Blues,</i>

203
00:09:13,219 --> 00:09:14,639
<i>Electric Laney Land,</i>

204
00:09:14,720 --> 00:09:16,140
<i>Laney Butchers The Beatles.</i>

205
00:09:16,222 --> 00:09:17,812
Ooh, and my favorite,

206
00:09:17,890 --> 00:09:20,600
<i>Rehab Yourself</i>
<i>A Merry Little Christmas.</i>

207
00:09:20,685 --> 00:09:22,055
I'll tell you what, Marge.

208
00:09:22,144 --> 00:09:24,864
I'll wipe the slate clean
on one condition.

209
00:09:24,939 --> 00:09:26,439
I want you to give Lisa to me.

210
00:09:26,524 --> 00:09:27,864
(grumbles)

211
00:09:27,942 --> 00:09:29,782
Uh, for a month or so.

212
00:09:33,322 --> 00:09:34,782
I see.

213
00:09:34,865 --> 00:09:38,115
Get out.
I never want to see you again.

214
00:09:38,202 --> 00:09:39,292
Let me explain.

215
00:09:39,370 --> 00:09:41,540
Listen, lady,
you can't take a daughter

216
00:09:41,622 --> 00:09:43,752
from a mother unless you're a bigger star

217
00:09:43,833 --> 00:09:46,173
and this is a third-world country.

218
00:09:46,252 --> 00:09:50,262
Marge, I know this sounds nuts,
but I never had the joy you have.

219
00:09:50,339 --> 00:09:52,589
A child to hug me at the end of the day

220
00:09:52,675 --> 00:09:55,175
or-or a chance
to pass along what I know.

221
00:09:55,261 --> 00:09:58,681
I'm going out on tour,
and she's got all the makings of a star:

222
00:09:58,764 --> 00:10:01,434
talent, smarts, and a star-shaped head.

223
00:10:01,517 --> 00:10:03,387
Perhaps you didn't hear me.

224
00:10:03,477 --> 00:10:05,767
Here's your coat.

225
00:10:05,855 --> 00:10:07,145
Mom, Mom.

226
00:10:07,231 --> 00:10:10,691
Mom, please. You were gonna
let me go to band camp for a month,

227
00:10:10,776 --> 00:10:13,736
where people break curfew
and exchange reeds.

228
00:10:13,821 --> 00:10:17,411
But this? This is the opportunity
to live my dream.

229
00:10:17,491 --> 00:10:20,701
Come on, how many chances
in life do you get for that?

230
00:10:20,786 --> 00:10:22,406
None!

231
00:10:22,496 --> 00:10:24,746
I've been here. I've just been quiet.

232
00:10:26,042 --> 00:10:27,292
♪ ♪

233
00:10:31,964 --> 00:10:34,884
(sighs)
I guess I can't deny you this.

234
00:10:34,967 --> 00:10:36,217
-All right.
-(gasps)

235
00:10:36,302 --> 00:10:37,932
Oh, thanks, Mom!

236
00:10:38,012 --> 00:10:40,932
And, Mom, if you have any doubts
how a showbiz kid will turn out,

237
00:10:41,015 --> 00:10:42,475
just look at all of them!

238
00:10:42,558 --> 00:10:44,058
(groans)

239
00:10:45,144 --> 00:10:46,734
(tires screech)

240
00:10:46,812 --> 00:10:48,732
Mom, I appreciate this so much.

241
00:10:48,814 --> 00:10:51,534
You'll be the first person
I thank at the Tonys

242
00:10:51,609 --> 00:10:53,569
after the great Angela Lansbury.

243
00:10:53,653 --> 00:10:55,073
Bye.

244
00:10:55,154 --> 00:10:56,784
(smoke hisses)

245
00:10:56,864 --> 00:10:58,414
(tires screech)

246
00:11:01,494 --> 00:11:04,084
(tires screech)

247
00:11:06,165 --> 00:11:08,665
Good night, kid.

248
00:11:08,751 --> 00:11:11,131
Would you read to me
before I go to bed?

249
00:11:11,212 --> 00:11:13,092
<i>Anne of Green Gables?</i>

250
00:11:13,172 --> 00:11:15,172
I did the audiobook on this.

251
00:11:15,257 --> 00:11:17,887
If chapter ten
sounds like it was Peter Falk,

252
00:11:17,968 --> 00:11:19,468
it's because it was.

253
00:11:19,553 --> 00:11:22,433
So I guess you don't want
to read it again.

254
00:11:22,515 --> 00:11:24,885
How 'bout I give you
some showbiz advice?

255
00:11:24,975 --> 00:11:27,435
Every piece of advice
someone gives you

256
00:11:27,520 --> 00:11:29,650
will turn out to be wrong.

257
00:11:29,730 --> 00:11:32,860
Particularly wrong are people like me,
who seem knowledgeable.

258
00:11:32,942 --> 00:11:34,902
Aw, she's already out.

259
00:11:35,945 --> 00:11:38,155
(phone rings)

260
00:11:38,239 --> 00:11:40,199
<i>MOE:</i>
<i>You watching Channel Six right now?</i>

261
00:11:40,282 --> 00:11:41,662
<i>Hurry up! Hurry up! Aw!</i>

262
00:11:41,742 --> 00:11:43,792
Nah, too late.
The cops cleaned it up.

263
00:11:43,869 --> 00:11:45,789
(piano playing)

264
00:11:45,871 --> 00:11:48,871
Chazz Busby.
My director.

265
00:11:48,958 --> 00:11:51,628
The man who's ruined more
productions than flu season.

266
00:11:51,711 --> 00:11:53,841
Laney! My star, my muse,

267
00:11:53,921 --> 00:11:55,801
my God,
what have you done to your face?

268
00:11:55,881 --> 00:11:57,261
(laughing)

269
00:11:57,341 --> 00:11:58,761
Who's the lampshade?

270
00:11:58,843 --> 00:11:59,973
This is Lisa Simpson,

271
00:12:00,052 --> 00:12:02,472
the sax prodigy who's gonna
blow life into my act.

272
00:12:02,555 --> 00:12:03,635
Show him, kid.

273
00:12:03,723 --> 00:12:05,063
(plays three notes)

274
00:12:05,141 --> 00:12:07,141
Whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa!
I wanted an audition,

275
00:12:07,226 --> 00:12:08,976
not a recital.
You're in, kid.

276
00:12:09,061 --> 00:12:10,731
I made it in Hartford.

277
00:12:14,525 --> 00:12:17,185
-Are you sure you set it up right?
-Yes!

278
00:12:17,278 --> 00:12:19,358
Then why aren't we Skyping?

279
00:12:19,447 --> 00:12:21,527
I don't know.
Maybe Lisa's drugged-out.

280
00:12:21,615 --> 00:12:23,905
My daughter is not drugged-out.

281
00:12:23,993 --> 00:12:26,833
Maybe she's just sleeping late
after partying at discotheques.

282
00:12:26,912 --> 00:12:29,462
How do you know
about all-night discotheques?

283
00:12:29,540 --> 00:12:31,920
We have Disco Stu in this town, Mom.

284
00:12:32,001 --> 00:12:34,001
He's a resource. Use him.

285
00:12:34,086 --> 00:12:35,666
(Skype ringtone plays)

286
00:12:35,755 --> 00:12:38,005
How are you, sweetie?

287
00:12:38,090 --> 00:12:39,590
<i>(gravelly)</i>
<i>I'm good, I'm good.</i>

288
00:12:39,675 --> 00:12:41,135
What happened to your voice?

289
00:12:41,218 --> 00:12:42,218
<i>I don't know.</i>

290
00:12:42,303 --> 00:12:43,893
<i>Late rehearsals, cheap root beer.</i>

291
00:12:43,971 --> 00:12:46,061
<i>(coughing)</i>

292
00:12:46,140 --> 00:12:48,430
<i>(normal voice) But I'm great!</i>
<i>We're heading to New York!</i>

293
00:12:49,518 --> 00:12:50,638
<i>(blows)</i>

294
00:12:50,728 --> 00:12:51,898
Who's watching you?

295
00:12:51,979 --> 00:12:53,189
<i>Sonny and Stix.</i>

296
00:12:53,272 --> 00:12:55,522
<i>(playing mellow jazz)</i>

297
00:12:55,608 --> 00:12:57,358
Do I hear syncopation?

298
00:12:57,443 --> 00:12:59,573
Lisa, Lisa, I was thinking
maybe you could

299
00:12:59,653 --> 00:13:01,573
come home a little early and...

300
00:13:01,655 --> 00:13:03,695
<i>I'm sorry. I got to go.</i>
<i>Our take five is over,</i>

301
00:13:03,783 --> 00:13:06,373
<i>and jazz is all about</i>
<i>following the rules, you know.</i>

302
00:13:06,452 --> 00:13:08,872
<i>Come on, guys.</i>
<i>Don't I get a puff?</i>

303
00:13:08,954 --> 00:13:10,294
(gasps)

304
00:13:11,707 --> 00:13:13,457
<i>I really have the munchies.</i>

305
00:13:13,542 --> 00:13:14,712
<i>(crunching)</i>

306
00:13:14,794 --> 00:13:16,174
<i>Bye!</i>

307
00:13:16,253 --> 00:13:18,013
We've got to get her back.

308
00:13:18,088 --> 00:13:20,418
Pack your things.
We're heading for New York.

309
00:13:20,508 --> 00:13:23,178
We should get a place there.
We go so often.

310
00:13:28,057 --> 00:13:29,477
♪ ♪

311
00:13:35,940 --> 00:13:38,940
I can't believe
I'm gonna be performing here.

312
00:13:39,026 --> 00:13:40,986
(dramatic music playing)

313
00:13:46,826 --> 00:13:49,446
I already got <i>my</i> ticket!

314
00:13:49,537 --> 00:13:51,537
LISA: (nervously)
Ah, so many seats.

315
00:13:51,622 --> 00:13:53,462
-(car sputtering)
-Damn it!

316
00:13:53,541 --> 00:13:55,081
Lousy electric car.

317
00:13:55,167 --> 00:13:57,627
Dad, just 'cause
it got hit by lightning that time

318
00:13:57,711 --> 00:13:59,171
doesn't make it electric.

319
00:13:59,255 --> 00:14:01,625
Shut up, boy.

320
00:14:06,512 --> 00:14:08,512
How may I help thee, friends?

321
00:14:08,597 --> 00:14:11,557
Our car... broketh down.

322
00:14:11,642 --> 00:14:13,982
(gasps)
Springfield Englisher accent?

323
00:14:14,061 --> 00:14:18,071
You must know
my ultra-liberal cousin Ned Flanders.

324
00:14:18,148 --> 00:14:20,608
Oh, he's brought such shame to our family

325
00:14:20,693 --> 00:14:23,073
with his lip hair and two marriages.

326
00:14:23,153 --> 00:14:26,533
And do you know he's left-handed?

327
00:14:26,615 --> 00:14:28,615
{\an8}(speaks foreign language)

328
00:14:28,701 --> 00:14:30,621
(wheels creaking)

329
00:14:32,872 --> 00:14:35,292
Um, can I please use the, uh,

330
00:14:35,374 --> 00:14:36,884
little bearded boys' room?

331
00:14:36,959 --> 00:14:38,039
(horse neighs)

332
00:14:38,127 --> 00:14:40,297
♪ ♪

333
00:14:50,639 --> 00:14:51,809
(humming)

334
00:14:51,891 --> 00:14:53,641
How deep did thou diggest?

335
00:14:53,726 --> 00:14:55,266
30 hands.

336
00:14:55,352 --> 00:14:57,982
With God's grace, it will be enough.

337
00:14:58,063 --> 00:15:01,363
<i>♪ Don't know why ♪</i>

338
00:15:01,442 --> 00:15:03,322
<i>♪ There's no sun up ♪</i>

339
00:15:03,402 --> 00:15:04,652
<i>♪ In the... ♪</i>

340
00:15:04,737 --> 00:15:07,317
<i>♪ In the... in the... ♪</i>

341
00:15:07,406 --> 00:15:09,866
How about "in the sky"?!
The sky!

342
00:15:09,950 --> 00:15:11,370
You ought to know, sweetheart.

343
00:15:11,452 --> 00:15:13,502
You were there when God created it.

344
00:15:13,579 --> 00:15:15,499
Eh, go shave a coconut.

345
00:15:15,581 --> 00:15:17,211
(gasping)

346
00:15:17,291 --> 00:15:19,921
I turned down <i>Transformers on Broadway</i>
for this?

347
00:15:20,002 --> 00:15:21,922
I was a Megatron-sized fool!

348
00:15:22,004 --> 00:15:25,094
Kristen Chenoweth was set to play
Sam Witwicky's mother.

349
00:15:25,174 --> 00:15:27,184
This is how mad I am!
Fade to black!

350
00:15:27,259 --> 00:15:29,009
You can't be serious!

351
00:15:29,094 --> 00:15:30,724
I said fade!

352
00:15:30,804 --> 00:15:33,184
Everyone, meet me back here
in however long it takes

353
00:15:33,265 --> 00:15:34,675
to wake up from five Valium.

354
00:15:34,767 --> 00:15:35,977
On the dot!

355
00:15:36,060 --> 00:15:37,520
(horns honking)

356
00:15:40,022 --> 00:15:42,272
Hey, man, how'd you get that seat?

357
00:15:42,358 --> 00:15:44,688
They thought I was pregnant.

358
00:15:46,779 --> 00:15:48,699
(indistinct chatter)

359
00:15:52,409 --> 00:15:55,369
It's showtime, Laney.
Time to see if there's still a spark left

360
00:15:55,454 --> 00:15:58,504
in that smoldering Duraflame log
you call a career.

361
00:16:00,042 --> 00:16:01,252
Hey, Laney.

362
00:16:01,335 --> 00:16:02,995
Moe, I need you.

363
00:16:03,087 --> 00:16:06,167
To make me feel confident,
strong and beautiful.

364
00:16:06,256 --> 00:16:08,626
Boy, I'm not real good
at boosting self-esteem there.

365
00:16:08,717 --> 00:16:11,427
But, uh, if you make a mistake,
I can fire my gun.

366
00:16:11,512 --> 00:16:13,562
And that's what the critics
will be yappin' about tomorrow.

367
00:16:13,639 --> 00:16:14,599
(chuckles)

368
00:16:20,562 --> 00:16:22,612
That's not encouragement!

369
00:16:22,690 --> 00:16:24,650
Those are your lyrics!

370
00:16:24,733 --> 00:16:27,573
-(applause, piano playing)
<i>-♪ I had a dream ♪</i>

371
00:16:27,653 --> 00:16:31,873
<i>♪ A dream about you, baby ♪</i>

372
00:16:31,949 --> 00:16:35,829
<i>♪ It's gonna come true, baby ♪</i>

373
00:16:35,911 --> 00:16:39,251
<i>♪ They think that we're through ♪</i>

374
00:16:39,331 --> 00:16:43,381
<i>♪ But, baby... ♪</i>

375
00:16:45,713 --> 00:16:48,263
<i>♪ You'll be swell ♪</i>

376
00:16:48,340 --> 00:16:50,180
<i>♪ You'll be great ♪</i>

377
00:16:50,259 --> 00:16:53,139
<i>♪ Gonna have the whole world on a... ♪</i>

378
00:16:53,220 --> 00:16:55,390
<i>♪ On a... ♪</i>

379
00:16:55,472 --> 00:16:56,812
Plate!

380
00:16:56,890 --> 00:16:58,020
(crowd cheering)

381
00:16:58,100 --> 00:16:59,940
Cheering for someone
getting a word right.

382
00:17:00,019 --> 00:17:01,519
That is a low bar.

383
00:17:01,603 --> 00:17:02,523
(panting)

384
00:17:02,604 --> 00:17:03,814
Four tickets, please.

385
00:17:03,897 --> 00:17:05,687
I'm sorry, ma'am.
The show is sold out

386
00:17:05,774 --> 00:17:07,694
for reasons that elude me.

387
00:17:07,776 --> 00:17:09,186
My daughter's in there.

388
00:17:09,278 --> 00:17:10,608
Eh, we all got our problems.

389
00:17:10,696 --> 00:17:13,736
I'm a ticket seller
for a dying art form.

390
00:17:13,824 --> 00:17:17,704
Hey, uh, you're a union man, right?

391
00:17:17,786 --> 00:17:19,366
Brother?

392
00:17:19,455 --> 00:17:20,655
Why didn't you say so?

393
00:17:20,748 --> 00:17:22,958
I have no choice now but to be corrupt.

394
00:17:23,042 --> 00:17:24,212
In you go.

395
00:17:25,377 --> 00:17:28,297
<i>LANEY:</i>
<i>♪ Everything's gonna be ♪</i>

396
00:17:28,380 --> 00:17:30,630
<i>♪ Bright lights and lollipops ♪</i>

397
00:17:30,716 --> 00:17:32,716
(playing jazz solo)

398
00:17:35,054 --> 00:17:37,974
(crowd cheering)

399
00:17:38,057 --> 00:17:40,017
Come on, let's sneak her out.

400
00:17:40,100 --> 00:17:42,980
Under the guise of soliciting
for Broadway Cares.

401
00:17:43,062 --> 00:17:45,112
(coins jingling)

402
00:17:46,648 --> 00:17:47,938
Wait. Wait, Homer.

403
00:17:48,025 --> 00:17:50,685
Look at our little girl.
She's got chops.

404
00:17:50,778 --> 00:17:52,908
Honest-to-goodness chops.

405
00:17:52,988 --> 00:17:55,738
Yeah.
Letting our daughter go on the road

406
00:17:55,824 --> 00:17:58,494
with an 80-year-old diva
and some sketchy jazz guys

407
00:17:58,577 --> 00:18:01,367
was the best decision
we ever made.

408
00:18:01,455 --> 00:18:05,165
<i>♪ Everything's coming up roses ♪</i>

409
00:18:05,250 --> 00:18:09,510
<i>♪ For me and for you! ♪</i>

410
00:18:09,588 --> 00:18:11,128
(crowd cheering)

411
00:18:12,174 --> 00:18:13,554
(whoops)

412
00:18:20,724 --> 00:18:22,484
Mom,
that was the greatest night of my life!

413
00:18:22,559 --> 00:18:23,639
MILHOUSE:
Hey!

414
00:18:23,727 --> 00:18:25,647
When does the show start?

415
00:18:25,729 --> 00:18:28,149
It did, and it was wonderful.

416
00:18:28,232 --> 00:18:30,732
Eh, she's been bitten
by the showbiz bug.

417
00:18:30,818 --> 00:18:33,198
And when that happens,
only working with Bruce Willis

418
00:18:33,278 --> 00:18:34,448
can extinguish it.

419
00:18:36,532 --> 00:18:37,742
(giggles)

420
00:18:37,825 --> 00:18:40,195
(sighs)
Okay. Just finish out the tour.

421
00:18:40,285 --> 00:18:42,785
We'll see you in Pittsfield.

422
00:18:48,127 --> 00:18:49,417
No way!

423
00:18:49,503 --> 00:18:52,013
Pittsfield ain't happening
for this little scene stealer.

424
00:18:52,089 --> 00:18:55,089
I love you, Lisa,
but you got a bigger ovation than me.

425
00:18:55,175 --> 00:18:57,505
So we can never
share the same stage again.

426
00:18:57,594 --> 00:18:59,604
What? How can you say that?

427
00:18:59,680 --> 00:19:01,600
Showbiz lesson
number seven:

428
00:19:01,682 --> 00:19:03,562
just when things are going great,

429
00:19:03,642 --> 00:19:05,562
they pull the rug
out from under you.

430
00:19:05,644 --> 00:19:07,404
Bad news, Laney.
We're shutting down.

431
00:19:07,479 --> 00:19:10,069
Never cleared the rights
to "Everything's Coming Up Roses."

432
00:19:10,149 --> 00:19:11,229
See what I mean?

433
00:19:11,316 --> 00:19:13,146
Also, we're gonna need that rug.

434
00:19:13,235 --> 00:19:16,025
-(grunts)
-(shouts)

435
00:19:16,113 --> 00:19:17,203
(sniffles)

436
00:19:17,281 --> 00:19:19,281
Mom,
suddenly I really want to go home.

437
00:19:19,366 --> 00:19:21,286
Oh. Mm.

438
00:19:21,368 --> 00:19:24,748
If you go,
let me give you one huge piece of advice:

439
00:19:24,830 --> 00:19:26,420
take the Eighth Avenue side,

440
00:19:26,498 --> 00:19:28,458
then catch a cab and circle back.

441
00:19:28,542 --> 00:19:30,422
And away... I... go!

442
00:19:30,502 --> 00:19:33,382
(scatting)
Pow!

443
00:19:33,463 --> 00:19:37,633
Well, Laney, youse, uh...
you still got me.

444
00:19:37,718 --> 00:19:39,638
{\an8}♪ ♪

445
00:20:00,073 --> 00:20:02,163
♪ ♪

446
00:20:02,242 --> 00:20:04,162
See how gaudy his house is?

447
00:20:04,244 --> 00:20:06,214
A brass doorknocker?

448
00:20:06,288 --> 00:20:08,288
Who lives here, Caligula?

449
00:20:08,373 --> 00:20:09,753
'Tis troubling.

450
00:20:09,833 --> 00:20:12,423
Cousin Jacob! All the way
from Pennsyl-diddly-vania!

451
00:20:12,502 --> 00:20:15,552
I see thou art still using
the Devil's "diddly."

452
00:20:15,631 --> 00:20:18,221
Well, I must confess, I-I do over-diddly.

453
00:20:18,300 --> 00:20:21,300
And I see your house
is lit by Edison's witch lights.

454
00:20:21,386 --> 00:20:25,176
(chuckles)
Who's holier than thou now, Ned?

455
00:20:25,265 --> 00:20:28,345
Homer, you've shown me
that I'm guilty of the sin of pride,

456
00:20:28,435 --> 00:20:30,845
and that just makes me love you more.

457
00:20:30,938 --> 00:20:33,898
Oh, God, I'm stuck in a Flandwich.

458
00:20:33,982 --> 00:20:35,822
With side orders of love and forgiveness!

459
00:20:35,901 --> 00:20:36,991
D'oh!

460
00:21:17,109 --> 00:21:19,149
-(murmuring)
-Shh!

461
00:21:22,030 --> 00:21:24,950
Subtitled by Jimmy Boots

